But what is more appalling is the denied reward for the homecare and the knock-on effect on the women’s socioeconomic being; and let us not rope in religion and the oppressive cultural regime as justification.
Work done is worth every penny, and should be compensated.
Beast of burden
Unpaid care and inequality undoubtedly cut across all trades in Kenya, but some counties are served a much shorter end of the stick.
 In Turkana County, which hosts some of the deepest forms of marginalisation and inequality in the country, is a hotbed of socioeconomic injustice among Kenya’s women folk.
Turkana women are a cultural beast of the burden. They have to fend for their families through menial work such as charcoal burning, basket weaving and basic ornament crafts.
This is in addition to taking care of animals, sick members of the family and the old folk. This situation hasn’t rung some alarm bells to the chieftains who continue to perpetuate the gender slavery doused in the cultural dogma of gender roles.



