I dare say, it is high time the calculus shifted and a new conversation on pay for work reborn. Homecare is work, whose time and investment is weighing down the Turkana woman, and that must sink for an equal society to be birthed.
But there are other trade burdens. Firstly, a Turkana woman trader, as indeed most women traders in Kenya, runs a small scale business across the vast rural county.
According to rudimentary statistics from the Turkana County’s Ministry of Trade, Gender and Youth Affairs, out of the 10,000 businesses recently audited in all the six sub-counties, just slightly over 1,000 are registered, a truly paltry statistic.
Marsabit County is yet to generate a meaningful data of registered businesses.
I know the precondition by the government for a business to qualify for a Covid-19 stimulus package is registration, as a formal step to recognition.
I’m aware that the instruments for cash transfers are formal, and as such, the business structures must be formal. Which is my biggest problem. We must assess the protocols for business formalisation. But the process is a costly venture. No, “cost” in the small informal business context means every extra sum of money, whatever sum, and that is what must be factored in the governments’ push for business formalisation.



