Marginalised businesses
To an indigenous Turkana woman, life is a hand-to-mouth affair. An extra cost is an extra burden, and a special consideration must suffice if the government is truly serious about fair and effective business safety-net to the low business cadres especially within the margins.
In a county like Turkana with over 80 percent illiteracy level (KNBS National census report 2019), a more moderated approach in business registration would be ideal. Business registration requires pin and certificate, tax instruments that the near entire rural women folk in Turkana barely fathoms.
Past practices seem to have only benefited small and medium enterprises, completely alienating the real hard hit population of the marginalised businesses.
Secondly, for the better part of the year, cross-border trade, which is the bastion of economy in the northern counties, was in shambles, thanks to the Covid-19 restrictions.
Borders were only open to essential goods and services, which came with its consequences. It may sound like I’m pitching for an illegality, but pragmatism is key here. Most cross-border businesses have been branded “smuggling” Because they have no formal identity.
But this a little off because illegality in the context of trade in the margins is not synonymous to theft, or robbery.



