The only “crime” is the business they ply, which is considered faceless with no registration. But haven’t they been trading centuries before the western formalisation consumed us?
Formalisation is a noble idea, but the governments, both county and national must incubate a working formulae to support these special groups of traders in their informal business ventures.
Indigenous traders
The sooner the governments took note of the massive disenfranchisement in the period of the borders closures by the Turkana indigenous traders, the better and realistic the response would be.
Finally, there is need to assess the gender dynamics in the distribution of funds. The problem with our systems is the toxic male domination. Give it any name, call it meritocracy, reflection of the society, natural selection and so on; but women are way past the pass mark. Women have the ability and quality to lead.





 They meet all the criteria; have the acumen and wherewithal to deliver. We must reorganise the systems that purport to address women’s needs. Women’s needs are better addressed by the women. Let governments have women at the centre of women’s emergency responses if they are serious about walking the talk.



